Part 6

The call came eleven days later, back at head office, in the middle of an unrelated meeting about tea packaging labels.

Vikram stepped out to take it.

"You won't believe this," Reddy said, and for once in his life sounded like he meant the phrase literally rather than as a figure of speech. "The MLA called Satyanarayana's office yesterday. Said to process the land allocation. No conditions."

"Why?"

"Nobody knows why. That's the part I don't believe. Man's been sitting on this file for two years, blocking it for reasons nobody could ever get straight, and now suddenly—" Reddy exhaled audibly down the line. "Doesn't matter. Take the win, Vikram. And it gets better. They've allotted double the acreage we asked for. Somebody upstairs must have decided to make it worth our while, or make up for lost time, or God knows what. I stopped trying to explain government logic years ago."

Vikram looked out through the glass wall of the corridor at the ordinary Tuesday traffic below, at people going about ordinary Tuesday errands with no idea that a two-year deadlock somewhere else had just, inexplicably, come undone.

"Vikram? You there? This is good news, in case that wasn't clear."

"I heard you, Reddy. It's good news."

"You don't sound like it's good news."

"I'm glad," Vikram said, and found, checking himself honestly, that he was — a clean, quiet gladness, without the fist-clenched triumph he might once have felt at the same news a year ago. "I just don't feel like I need to do anything about being glad. Does that make sense?"

"No," Reddy said. "But congratulations anyway."

---

That evening, alone in the hotel room he still hadn't gotten used to, Vikram found the folded paper again, in the inside pocket where he'd been carrying it without quite noticing he had.

He sat the way it showed, for the ten minutes it said, no more.

He didn't feel transformed. He didn't feel anything sudden or cinematic.

He felt, mostly, like a man who had stopped needing the outcome to arrive on time in order to keep doing the work anyway — which, he suspected, without being able to say exactly why, was the entire point of the exercise, and probably the entire point of the word he'd been given, still not fully understanding it, still not needing to.

Somewhere past the hotel's window, past the city, past several states, a fire was probably still burning at the edge of a coffee plantation, tended by a man who would likely never know what his ash and his silence had helped set in motion.

Vikram didn't call to tell him.

Some things, he was beginning to understand, weren't owed an explanation. Not even a grateful one.

He went back to his files that night lighter than he had in years, and the land, when it finally came through on paper three weeks later, felt less like a victory than like a fact he'd already made peace with in advance.
